\section*{Summary and outstanding challenges}

\begin{frame}{Concluding remarks}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    The theory \emph{corrects} and \emph{strictly extends} all existing likelihood-based phylodynamic methods \citep[\eg][]{Volz2009a,Rasmussen2011,Stadler2010,Volz2012,Volz2014a,Rasmussen2014a,Vaughan2019}.
  \item
    It eliminates the need for large population-size and small sample-fraction assumptions, as well as any dependence on linearization.
  \item
    All computations can be carried out forward in time.
  \item
    This greatly expands the class of models that can be entertained.
  \item
    Great flexibility in sampling model
  \item
    Applications in disease ecology and beyond
  \item
    The unstructured case can be found in \citet{King2022}.
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Outstanding challenges}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Choice of importance-sampling kernel
  \item Borrowing information from future is allowed.
  \item Phylogenetic uncertainty
  \item Efficient algorithms
  \item Reassortment and recombination
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Summary}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item A discretely structured Markov population process uniquely induces a genealogy-valued Markov process.
  \item The likelihood of an observed genealogy satisfies a nonlinear filtering equation, which can be efficiently computed via Feynman-Ka\c{c} (sequential Monte Carlo) algorithms.
  \item In principle, these results liberate us to entertain models that more closely match our biological questions, without less hindrance from inference methodology.
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

